  ('Double Dumbbell Front Squat', 'double-dumbbell-front-squat', 'Double Dumbbell Front Squat is a dumbbell-loaded strength exercise for lower-body force production. Load, range, tempo, and rest should support force production rather than metabolic fatigue.', 'BEGINNER', 8, 3, 6, 40, 120, 160, 'Two-dumbbell front-rack squat that increases loading potential and trunk demand. Strength is the primary score; explosiveness is delivery-dependent, not the main intent.', 'Primary subrole: Squat / knee-dominant strength. Score Strength high. Add a small Explosiveness score only when the coach uses crisp concentric intent, low fatigue, and adequate rest; do not treat it as a jump, plyometric, or conditioning station.', 'Set position first, move the dumbbell with control, then finish every rep like you could repeat it cleanly.', 'Squat / Knee-Dominant Strength', 'capacity', 'squat_knee_dominant_strength', 'double_dumbbell_front_squat_strength', '{"primary_joint_actions":["hip_flexion","knee_flexion","ankle_dorsiflexion","front_rack_bracing","hip_extension","knee_extension"],"primary_tissues":["quadriceps","gluteals","upper_back","anterior_core"],"primary_motor_control_demands":["bracing","position_ownership","load_path_control"],"postural_shape":"stacked_ribs_over_pelvis_with_task_specific_joint_positions","breathing_demand":"braced_exhale_on_effort","balance_demand":"stable","coordination_demand":"moderate_strength_patterning","impact_level":0}'::jsonb, '{"movement_description":"Double Dumbbell Front Squat: Two-dumbbell front-rack squat that increases loading potential and trunk demand. Use load that lets the athlete control the entire rep and finish with the same alignment they started with.","setup":["Select dumbbell load that allows full control for Double Dumbbell Front Squat.","Set feet and stance before lifting the weight into position.","Brace ribs over pelvis and keep eyes forward.","Own the start position before the first rep."],"execution_steps":["Lower with control through the usable range while keeping knees tracking over the feet.","Drive the floor away and stand tall without bouncing or losing trunk position.","Reset breathing and tension between reps when load is challenging.","Stop the set when depth, alignment, or bracing changes."],"coach_cues":["Own the setup before the rep.","Brace, then move the dumbbell.","Control down; drive up without losing shape.","Stop before strength turns into survival."],"common_faults":["Chasing load before position is repeatable.","Holding the breath for the entire set instead of bracing and breathing.","Rushing the eccentric or bouncing out of the bottom.","Knees collapse inward or heels lose pressure."]}'::jsonb),
